What broke: You called .map() on a variable that is undefined instead of an array.
Why it broke: The variable was never assigned a value, or a function returned undefined instead of the array you expected.
How to fix: Add a check to make sure the variable is an array before calling .map() on it.
Example fix:
const items = data?.items || [];
items.map(item => console.log(item));

What broke: You used a variable that has never been declared anywhere in scope.
Why it broke: JavaScript cannot find any let, const, or var declaration for this variable name in the current or parent scopes.
How to fix: Declare the variable before using it with let, const, or var.
Example fix:
let count = 0;
console.log(count);

What broke: JavaScript found a closing curly brace where it did not expect one.
Why it broke: There is a mismatched bracket somewhere in your code — either an extra closing brace or a missing opening brace.
How to fix: Count your opening and closing curly braces carefully. Most code editors highlight matching brackets.
Example fix:
function greet() {
    console.log('hello');
}  // every opening { needs a closing }

What broke: You tried to call something as a function but it is not a function.
Why it broke: Either the variable holds a string, number, or object instead of a function, or you misspelled the function name.
How to fix: Check what type the variable actually holds using console.log(typeof X) before calling it.
Example fix:
console.log(typeof myVar);  // check if it's actually a function
if (typeof myVar === 'function') {
    myVar();
}

What broke: A function kept calling itself infinitely until JavaScript ran out of call stack space.
Why it broke: You have infinite recursion — a function that calls itself with no stopping condition, or the stopping condition is never reached.
How to fix: Add a base case that stops the recursion, or rewrite the logic using a loop instead.
Example fix:
function countdown(n) {
    if (n <= 0) return;  // base case stops recursion
    countdown(n - 1);
}

What broke: You tried to set innerHTML on an element but the element is null meaning it was not found in the page.
Why it broke: document.getElementById() returns null when no element with that ID exists. This usually means a typo in the ID name or the script runs before the HTML loads.
How to fix: Check the element ID spelling and make sure your script runs after the HTML is loaded.
Example fix:
document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
    const el = document.getElementById('myDiv');
    if (el) el.innerHTML = 'Hello';
});

What broke: JavaScript reached the end of your file but expected more code, usually a closing bracket or brace.
Why it broke: You have unclosed parentheses, brackets, or curly braces somewhere in your code.
How to fix: Check for missing closing brackets at the end of functions, objects, or arrays.
Example fix:
const obj = {
    name: 'Alice'
};  // don't forget closing }

What broke: You tried to add an event listener to an element that does not exist on the page.
Why it broke: The element was not found, either because the ID is wrong, the element does not exist yet, or the script runs before the HTML is rendered.
How to fix: Wrap your code in DOMContentLoaded to ensure HTML is ready, and verify the element ID is correct.
Example fix:
document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
    document.getElementById('btn').addEventListener('click', handleClick);
});

What broke: The fetch API is not available in the environment where your code is running.
Why it broke: fetch is a browser API not available in older Node.js versions or certain restricted environments.
How to fix: In Node.js install the node-fetch package, or use the built-in fetch available in Node 18 and above.
Example fix:
// Node.js below 18
const fetch = require('node-fetch');
fetch('https://api.example.com');

What broke: Your browser blocked a network request because the server did not give permission for your website to access it.
Why it broke: Browsers enforce CORS security policy which prevents websites from making requests to different domains unless the server explicitly allows it.
How to fix: This needs to be fixed on the server side by adding CORS headers. For development you can use a proxy.
Example fix:
// In your Express server
app.use((req, res, next) => {
    res.header('Access-Control-Allow-Origin', '*');
    next();
});

What broke: Your code tried to use an object that is null as if it had a value.
Why it broke: A variable was declared but never assigned an actual object, or a method returned null and you used the result without checking.
How to fix: Always check if an object is null before calling methods on it.
Example fix:
String name = getName();
if (name != null) {
    System.out.println(name.length());
}

What broke: You tried to access position 5 in an array that only has 3 elements.
Why it broke: Java arrays are zero-indexed so a 3-element array has valid indexes 0, 1, and 2 only.
How to fix: Always use array.length to check the size before accessing elements.
Example fix:
int[] arr = {10, 20, 30};
for (int i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {
    System.out.println(arr[i]);
}

What broke: A method kept calling itself or other methods in an endless chain until Java ran out of stack space.
Why it broke: You have infinite recursion with no base case, or two methods keep calling each other in an endless loop.
How to fix: Find the recursive call and add a proper base case that stops the recursion.
Example fix:
public int factorial(int n) {
    if (n <= 1) return 1;  // base case
    return n * factorial(n - 1);
}

What broke: You tried to convert the text 'abc' into a number but it is not a valid number.
Why it broke: Integer.parseInt() and similar methods can only handle strings that contain actual numeric digits.
How to fix: Validate the string before converting or wrap in try-catch.
Example fix:
try {
    int num = Integer.parseInt(input);
} catch (NumberFormatException e) {
    System.out.println('Please enter a valid number');
}

What broke: You called a React hook like useState inside an if statement or loop.
Why it broke: React requires hooks to always be called in the same order on every render. Calling them conditionally breaks this rule and causes unpredictable behavior.
How to fix: Move all hook calls to the top level of your component, outside of any conditions or loops.
Example fix:
function MyComponent() {
    const [count, setCount] = useState(0);  // always at top level
    if (someCondition) {
        // use count here, not useState
    }
}

What broke: You called a state setter function directly during the render phase of another component.
Why it broke: Calling setState during render causes an infinite update loop because setting state triggers a re-render which calls setState again.
How to fix: Move state updates into event handlers or useEffect hooks, never call them directly during render.
Example fix:
useEffect(() => {
    setCount(newValue);  // safe - runs after render
}, [dependency]);
